ce:section.ce:para:
Based on the accumulation of previous studies in our group [34,35], in this paper, S-type NCN/CdS heterojunction nanomaterials were synthesized by anchoring cadmium sulfide on nitrogen-doped quantum dot-modified g-C3N4 (Scheme 1
                     ). Its performance for selective detection and efficient degradation of TC and CTC was also examined. Fluorescence sensing experiments have shown that NCN/CdS can detect TC and CTC via fluorescence quenching with good selectivity and high sensitivity. Transient fluorescence spectroscopy and UV–vis absorption spectroscopy suggest that the mechanism of NCN/CdS detection of TC and CTC may be an internal filter effect (IFE). Meanwhile, The S-type heterojunction has a strong redox capacity and effectively separates photogenerated e−-h+ pairs, which improves photocatalytic performance. NCDs act as charge-bridging channels at the heterojunction interface to further accelerate carrier separation. Therefore, NCN/CdS can efficiently degrade TC and CTC. Possible TC and CTC degradation pathways were detected and investigated using liquid-mass spectrometry (LC-MS). Furthermore, free radical trapping experiments and electron paramagnetic resonance (EPR) spectroscopy determined that holes (h+) and superoxide radicals (•O2
                     −) play a dominant role in the photocatalytic degradation process. In summary, the development of cheap and reusable g-C3N4-based nanomaterials for selective detection and efficient degradation of TC and CTC in the environment is of great theoretical and practical significance.
